[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction to Variations"]
[Result "*"]

{ This Book is dedicated to my Mother. The Queen who always accepted the gambit.  In this chapter we shall list the different move orders and variations in order to help the reader navigate through all the chapters. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3
{ Please note that:   3.Nc3  c5  4.d5  leads to the Linares Variation;   3.Nc3  a6  leads to Chess Explained Variation;   3.e3  c5  4.Nf3  leads to the Annoying Variation;   3.Nf3  c5  4.d5  leads to the Seirawan Variation;   3.e4  c5  4.d5  leads to the Linares Variation;   3.e4  c5  4.Nf3  leads to the endgames. }
3... c5
{ This is our standard 3rd move. We shall always play 3... c5 attacking the center against any move, save Qa4+ when it is illegal. }
4. Bxc4
{ Having shown the other lines we shall briefly navigate to the classical lines. Please note that against all moves save  3.e4  we have the option to go into these lines. It is therefore imperative that we understand the structures and ideas that these lines presents.  Conversely the reader will almost always have the option to avoid the main lines by playing 3... cxd4. }
4... e6
{ We take control over d5.   Please note that here to we have the option to go into the Annoying lines by playing  4. ...cxd4  5.exd4  Qc7. }
5. Nf3 Nf6 { Normal development preparing to castle. } 6. O-O a6
{ This is the start of the classical lines. White can play   7.a4   7.Qe2  or the sneaky   7.Bb3 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Lenderman, Aleksandr vs. Anton Guijarro, David"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game shows a number of the ideas in this book. This is a fantastic example of how to grind to the win. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6
{ Our repertoire would have played  3. ...c5  4.e3  cxd4  entering into the annoying variation. }
4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 { We entered the Classical lines. } 6. O-O a6 7. Bb3
{ Lenderman opts for the Sneaky Sneaky variation ... @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/variation/4989275/@@LinkEnd@@ }
7... b5 { Our proponent is fearless and follows our recommendation. } 8. Qe2
{ Lenderman backs down and does not play  8.a4  but rather goes the traditional route similar to @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/variation/3145506/@@LinkEnd@@ }
8... Bb7 9. Rd1 Nbd7 10. e4
{ This is the third most popular move in the position and, save for this game, is not covered in our book. The more popular  10.Nc3  is covered as @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/variation/3145506/@@LinkEnd@@ and the second more popular line  10.a4  is covered as @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/variation/3144922/@@LinkEnd@@ }
10... cxd4
{ This move is very much in keeping with the general philosophy of this book. The silicon engines, at low depth, prefer the materialistic Bxe4 but then at higher depth starts to prefer the text. }
11. Nxd4 Qc7 12. Nc3 Bc5 13. Be3 O-O
{ This is a structure and piece placement which the reader will see often in the first chapters of this book. We will sometimes prefer Qb8 and our bishop will normally go to d6 or e7. }
14. Rac1 Qb6 15. f3 Rac8 16. Bf2 Ne5
{ Our knight occupies what I like to call our launch pad. The occupation of this square, normally with the knight, is often the prelude to seizing the initiative. see ex @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/variation/4038055/@@LinkEnd@@ }
17. Rc2 Nh5 18. g3 Nf6 19. Rcd2 h6 20. Kg2 g5
{ This structure on the kingside is very desirable @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/variation/4068432/#/15/b/@@LinkEnd@@ }
21. h3 Ng6 22. Be3 Rfe8 23. Nc2 Bxe3 24. Qxe3 Qxe3 25. Nxe3
{ Into the endgame and see how we grind. } 25... h5 26. g4 h4
{ Inaccuracy. Best move was Kg7. } 27. a3 Kf8 28. Ne2 Rc7 29. Nd4 Rec8 30. Kh2
{ White is no longer playing for the win. However because of all the weaknesses Black is able to make progress. }
30... Ke7 31. Kg2 Ne5 32. Rc2 Rxc2+ 33. Bxc2 Nfd7 34. Bd3 Ng6 35. Kf2 Nde5 36.
Bf1 Nf4
{ Just look at how much pressure those knights are placing on the White position. Conversely look at how bad the light squared bishop is. }
37. Nb3 Rc7 38. Rd2 Bc8 39. Rd1 Bd7 40. Rd2 Be8 41. Rd1
{ Blunder. Best move was Nd4. } 41... b4 42. Ra1 bxa3 43. Rxa3 Bb5 44. Ra5 Bxf1
45. Kxf1 Rb7 46. Nd4 Rxb2 47. Nec2 Rb1+ 48. Kf2 Nxh3+ 49. Kg2 Nf4+ 50. Kh2 Kf6
51. Rxa6 Rd1 52. Ra3 Rd2+ 53. Kh1 Ned3 54. Ra1 Rg2 55. Ne3
{ Checkmate is now unavoidable. Best move was Rf1. } 55... Nf2# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. The Classical 7. a4 "]
[Black "The Classical 7. a4 #1: The Dubious 8. Nc3."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Welcome to the first of our chapters on the classical lines of the QGA. In this chapter we shall explore the old main line of 7. a4.Understanding these classical chapters will help you understand many of the ideas in the other chapters but it should be pointed out that most of our recommendations are deliberately trying to avoid these lines in favour of taking White out of book. }
2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Bxc4 e6
{ As pointed out earlier we can avoid these lines and transpose to the Annoying line from here by playing  4...cxd4  5.exd4  Qc7. }
5. Nf3 Nf6 6. O-O a6 7. a4 Nc6 8. Nc3 { This is a common mistake. } 8... Be7
{ Black could just continue with  8...Qc7  but this line gives clear equality. In fact it is White that needs to play perfectly to retain equality. }
9. Qe2
{ White continues as normal but the alternatives does not help, for example  9.Re1  O-O  and we will develop normally. The rook on e1 is a bit lost in space. }
9... cxd4 { Boom! } 10. Rd1
{ 10.exd4  Nxd4  11.Nxd4  Qxd4  12.Rd1  Qg4  and White does not have enough for the center pawn. }
10... e5 11. exd4 exd4 { Now the point of 8... Be7 is seen. } 12. Nxd4
{ A common mistake here is  12.Be3  which is very well met with  12...Bg4! }
12... Nxd4 13. Qe5 Qd6 { White is forced to exchange the queens. } 14. Qxd6
Bxd6 15. Rxd4 Bc5 16. Rd1 O-O
{ This is the position that has lead to many GM draws. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. The Classical 7. a4 "]
[Black "The Classical 7. a4 #2: The modern 8. b3."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Bxc4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. O-O a6 7. a4 Nc6 8. b3
{ This is the modern approach. Naturally White can start by taking on c5 then playing b3. Those positions will be looked at in our endgame lines. }
8... cxd4
{ It makes simple sense to me to create an IQP that blocks the bishop in these lines. }
9. exd4
{ No other recapture really helps White. In fact Black would like to trade as many pieces as possible and get into the endgame with the IQP and the bishop stuck behind it. }
9... Be7 { I prefer simple development from here. } 10. Bb2 O-O
{ Black is already arguably better. The only problem is the light squared bishop. Our development will include Qc7, b6 and Bb7 in some order.The knight on c6 will either go to d5 via b4 or exchange itself for the bishop on c4 via a5. The former plan is the slower solid approach whereas the latter is the more risky approach.Personally I believe that Nb4-d5 is easy to play for a risk free advantage in the form of the IQP. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. The Classical 7. a4 "]
[Black "The Classical 7. a4 #3: The reason for h3."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Bxc4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. O-O a6 7. a4 Nc6 8. Qe2
Qc7 9. Nc3 Be7 10. Rd1 O-O 11. e4 { White neglects h3 and we can punish this. }
11... Ng4 12. h3
{ This move does not help - in fact it is just a wasted tempo.   Please note that after  12.dxc5  Bc5  the f2-square is also now attacked. }
12... Nxd4 { Everything comes with tempo. The attack plays itself. } 13. Rxd4
{ White is forced to go into this but it is only Black that is better. } 13...
cxd4 14. hxg4 dxc3 { Black is up an exchange for nothing. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. The Classical 7. a4 "]
[Black "The Classical 7. a4 #4: White plays 12 dxc5 going for the e4 push."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Bxc4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. O-O a6 7. a4
{ White stops b5 but give us the nice square b4 for our knight. } 7... Nc6
{ We develop our knight with an eye on b4. } 8. Qe2
{ If White gets his move order wrong by playing  8.Nc3  Be7  9.Qe2  then we can punish him with  9. ...cxd4  10.Re1  e5!  and White has to play perfectly for equality, as we saw in the the first line of this chapter. }
8... Qc7
{ We continue with the waiting game.   Alternatively  8...Be7  is playable but we want to move our bishop to c5 in one go. }
9. Rd1
{ White also waits because he knows that ...cxd4 gives him a IQP and is playable for Black, but it frees the White bishop on c1. }
9... Be7
{ Alternatives are  9...cxd4   and  9...Bd6.  I prefer the text move because after Bd6 we are forced to take immediately on c5 whereas ...Be7 sometimes allow the in-between move ...Ng4. On the other hand ...cxd4 leads to positions where Black needs to play Nb4-d5 then suffer a long attack before the IQP becomes relevant.   If you dont like the main variations that I give then you should consider  9...cxd4. }
10. Nc3 { White can still wait with taking a decision in the center. } 10...
O-O 11. h3
{ White wants to play e4 to liberate the bishop on c1 but the immediate   11.e4  runs into  11...Ng4  and if  12.h3?  then  12...Nxd4! }
11... b6 { We have to get our problem bishop out. } 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. e4 Bb7
{ We develop our problem piece.  13...Nfd7  is also possible after which White can continue with the pawn sacrifice  14.e5. }
14. e5 Nh5
{ The old  14. ...Nd7  was based on a suggestion in an old book. It seems now, thanks to the engines, that White has a good piece sacrifice in the final position. It is for this reason that we now go for this strange sharp line which is engine approved.   Our threat is to go to g3 and harass the queen. Surprisingly she has no good place to go. }
15. Kf1
{ Moving out of the pin and preparing g4 but making the g3 square so juicy.  White has the option of sacrificing the e-pawn for the bishop pair but the engines gives equality:   15.Ne4  Nxe5  16.Nxe5  Qxe5  17.Nxc5  Qxc5  Please note that:   15.g4  Ng3 }
15... Ne7
{ Our knight is going to the juicy square. Please note how all our minor pieces are contributing into the attack. }
16. Bd3
{ White has to bring the bishop to stop Nf5 and to threaten Bxh7+ followed by Ng5+.  Please note:   16.Ne4  Nf5  17.Bg5?  Bxe4!   16.g4  Qc6 }
16... Ng6
{ We have to change our focus now to the f4 square and the two bishop advantage. }
17. Be4 Rac8 { Activating the rook. } 18. Bxb7 { White has nothing better! }
18... Qxb7
{ White has no constructive plan here. Eventually the queens will come off  (most likely on e4)  and then our knight on h5 will rejoin the fight from f4.  The engines still like White but I believe Black is easier to play and we shall be looking at that pawn on e5 somewhere in the future. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. The Classical 7. a4 "]
[Black "The Classical 7. a4 #5: White Plays 12 d5 for the central break through."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Bxc4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. O-O a6 7. a4 Nc6 8. Qe2
Qc7 9. Rd1 Be7 10. Nc3 O-O 11. h3 b6 12. d5
{ White wants to break open the center and try to take advantage of the a8-h1 diagonal. }
12... exd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Bb7 { We develop our problem piece. } 15. e4
{ This frees the bishop on c1. } 15... Bf6
{ Putting pressure on b2 and keeping an eye on e5. } 16. Be3 Rfe8
{ We want the e-pawn to stay where it is. } 17. Rac1 Nb4
{ After the exchanges Black is fine. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. The Classical 7. a4 "]
[Black "Model game #1: Vladimirov, Evgeny (2575) vs. Illescas Cordoba, Miguel (2545)"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game is a clear illustration that the endgame favours Black because of the queenside majority. This is a common idea through most of the endgame variations. }
1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 c6 4. e3 e6 5. Bd3 dxc4 6. Bxc4 c5 7. O-O a6 8. a4
Nc6 9. Qe2 Be7 10. Rd1 Qc7 11. Nc3 O-O
{ We have reached our starting position even though it has been a slightly uncommon move order. }
12. h3
{ This is a game from the 1990's and the next few moves were not precise. }
12... Rd8 13. Ba2 b6 14. d5 { White goes for the d5 break. } 14... exd5 15.
Bxd5 Nxd5 16. Nxd5
{ Please note how Black keeps exchanging pieces. He knows that his queenside majority becomes more of an issue as the pieces come off. }
16... Qb7 17. e4
{ Finally White gets to play e4 to free his dark square bishop. } 17... Be6 18.
Bf4 Bf8 19. Nc7 { This just helps Black with his cause. } 19... Rxd1+ 20. Rxd1
Bb3 21. Nxa8 Bxd1 22. Qxd1 Qxa8
{ The dust has settled and most of the pieces have come off. If the queens come off then the Black majority will rule the day.Black threatens Qd8 taking the file or exchanging queens. }
23. Qd7 Ne7
{ ...b5 is very desirable move but the threat of e5-e6 needs to be addressed. }
24. Bd6
{ Still White goes for simplifications, while only Black benefits from this. }
24... Qxe4 25. Qd8 Ng6 26. Bxf8 Nxf8 27. Qxb6 Qxa4 28. Ne5 Qd1+ 29. Kh2 Qd4 30.
Nc6 Qd6+ 31. Kg1 Qd1+ 32. Kh2 Qd6+ 33. Kg1 Ne6 34. Qxa6 g6 35. Qa4 Qd2 36. Qb5
Kg7 37. g3 h5 38. h4 Qd1+ 39. Qf1 Qa4 40. Ne5 Qe4 41. f4 Nd4 42. Qc4 Qb1+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. The Classical 7 Qe2"]
[Black "The Recommended 7. Bb3"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this Chapter we shall look at lines where White does not play a4 immediately but rather waits for b5 by Black or leaves it out completely. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Bxc4 e6
{ Please note that this whole chapter can be avoided, if you so wish, by playing   4. ...cxd4 }
5. Nf3 Nf6 6. O-O a6 7. Bb3
{ Sneaky Sneaky... This, essentially a waiting move, is often recommended. The thinking is that Black now has to commit to either   7. ...cxd4   or  7. ...Be7  losing a tempo   or  7. ...b5 }
7... b5
{ We show no fear. The point is that, with the exception of the line under review, we will always transpose to our classical lines. }
8. a4
{ This is the only real line of independent value. White goes for the minority attack whiles Black is still trying to get his king to safety. }
8... c4
{ We fight fire with fire. This is not grinding to a halt but grinding to a win. }
9. Bc2 Bb7 10. axb5 axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8
{ White has exchanged a lot of material hoping that our b-pawn will become weak. Black on the other hand wants to get the king to safety then try to push the b-pawn down. It is all about the b-pawn ... b-pawn ... no problem. }
12. b3
{ White prevents the pawns from returning to their natural state. ie.   12.Nc3  b4 }
12... cxb3
{ With the exchange of these pawns our b-pawn becomes the sole of the position. }
13. Bxb3 Be7
{ We continue with our plan. If left undisturbed we shall get our King to safety then support the b-pawn in its quest to ruin the White position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. The Classical 7 Qe2"]
[Black "The Classical 7. Qe2 #1: 8 Bd3 and the IQP"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Bxc4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. O-O a6 7. Qe2
{ This is the absolute classical line. White allows Black to play ...b5 but hopes to punish this advance later. If you are lazy and only want to do one chapter in this book then this is it. You can always steer the game into this chapter save for the lines 3. e4 and 7. a4.On the other hand it is our intention to avoid these variations by way of our recommendations. Not because these lines are bad for Black but because we are trying to take White out of his comfort zone with sharp confusing lines. }
7... b5 8. Bd3
{ This move sets up some traps and we are forced to take on d4. As a general rule in these positions I always take on d4 unless the bishop retreated to b3. }
8... cxd4 9. exd4
{ White has an IQP and Black can look forward to a good endgame. The only issue is he has to get to that endgame first! }
9... Bb7 10. a4
{ White must attack as soon as possible. He should not give Black the time to develop his pieces and move his king to safety. }
10... bxa4 { We dont want a weakness on b5 or b4. } 11. Rxa4 Be7
{ The best place for the bishop and intending to castle short. } 12. Nc3 O-O
{ Finally. } 13. Bg5 Nc6
{ We don't want passive defence. Our plan now is ...a5 then ...Nb4 winning a tempo against the bishop and then thereafter Nd5 placing the IQP under lock and key.  Noteworthy is the fact that Nc6 stops Ne5 by putting pressure on d4. Also   14.Bxa6  Bxa6  15.Rxa6  Rxa6  15.Qxa6  Nxd4  favours Black because we are slightly better developed and we have a target in the b-pawn. }
14. Rd1 a5 15. Bxf6
{ White gives the bishop pair in order to get rid of his problem pawn. } 15...
Bxf6 16. d5 exd5 17. Nxd5 { We have to give the bishop pair back. } 17... g6
{ We want to try and hold on to the bishop pair. This move also stops some ideas with Bxh7+. Please note that Black loses material in case of   17...Kh8?  18.Be4. }
18. Bb5 { Now  18.Be4  is too late and can just be answered by  18...Bg7. }
18... Kh8
{ This is the only move that does not draw or lose by force.   18...Na7  19.Bc4  Nc6  20.Bb5  Na7  is a draw.   18...Bg7 ?  19.Bxc6  Bxc6  20.Ne7+  loses. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. The Classical 7 Qe2"]
[Black "The Classical 7. Qe2 #2: The IQP and White does nothing special"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Bxc4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. O-O a6 7. Qe2 b5 8. Bd3
cxd4 9. exd4 Bb7 10. Nc3
{ If White just develops normally we will try to exchange pieces into an endgame where the IQP becomes relevant. }
10... Be7 11. Rd1 O-O 12. Bg5 Nbd7 { This is our normal setup. } 13. Rac1 Nd5
{ Now White cannot avoid exchanges. Black is better here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. The Classical 7 Qe2"]
[Black "The Classical 7. Qe2 #3: 8 Bb3 and Minority Attack"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Bxc4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. O-O a6 7. Qe2 b5 8. Bb3
{ This is the most popular move. b3 is probably the best place for the bishop. }
8... Bb7 9. a4
{ White immediately begins with its minority attack on the queenside. If Black can get his pieces out and his king safe without any disaster then he will be fine. }
9... Nbd7 { Here we do not take on a4 because the bishop can recapture. } 10.
axb5 axb5 11. Rxa8 Qxa8
{ We take with the queen putting pressure on the knight and indirectly protecting the b5 pawn. }
12. Nc3 Bxf3 13. gxf3
{ White does not want to go into an endgame where our king is more active and our structure is better. }
13... b4 14. Nb5 Qb8 { We have to cover c7. } 15. Rd1 Be7
{ Working towards castling. } 16. e4
{ White now wants to break open the centre. } 16... cxd4
{ This move deals with the threat of d5 and gets our bishop to a better diagonal. }
17. Nxd4 Bd6 18. h3 O-O { Black is fine. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. The Classical 7 Qe2"]
[Black "The Classical 7. Qe2 #4: The minority attack - 13. Qxf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Bxc4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. O-O a6 7. Qe2 b5 8. Bb3
Bb7 9. a4 Nbd7 10. axb5 axb5 11. Rxa8 Qxa8 12. Nc3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3
{ The exchange of queens does not really help White's chances. } 13... Qxf3 14.
gxf3 cxd4 { We resolve the tension in the center to our advantage. } 15. Nxb5
dxe3 16. fxe3
{ White undoubles his pawns but we still have the better structure. } 16... Bc5
{ Now the endgame battle begins. We have the structure whereas White has the two bishops. The battle will rage on for the b-pawn. Black is not worse here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. The Classical 7 Qe2"]
[Black "The Classical 7. Qe2 #5: 8 Bb3 Central Attack"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Bxc4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. O-O a6 7. Qe2 b5 8. Bb3
Bb7 9. Rd1 { White decides to play for the center break instead. } 9... Nbd7
10. Nc3 Qb8
{ Black has many moves here. eg. ...Qc7 or ...Qb6. I prefer the old ...Qb8 because we are ready to meet the delayed a4 and the delayed dxc5. }
11. d5 c4
{ Naturally taking on d5 is very possible but we playing for a win here. } 12.
dxe6 fxe6 13. Bc2 Bd6
{ Our bishop goes to the most aggressive square. The point is that the knights are connected and also we have to take full advantage of the placing of our queen. }
14. e4 { White frees his bishop. } 14... O-O
{ Now we ready to start counter attacking. } 15. h3 Qc7
{ This move connects the rooks. It seems as if we lost a tempo but White no longer has the option of opening the c-file so this is were we put our queen.   Please note  15...Ne5  does not work because White is not forced to take but can play  16.Ng5  ,  attacking e6, and follow it up with 17. f4. }
16. Nd4 Rae8
{ We protect the e6 square  (and pawn)  with this rook and now we are ready to attack on the kingside with moves such as ...Ne5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. The Classical 7 Qe2"]
[Black "The Classical 7. Qe2 #6: The Center attack - White neglects h3."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Bxc4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. O-O a6 7. Qe2 b5 8. Bb3
Bb7 9. Rd1 Nbd7 10. Nc3 Qb8 11. d5 c4 12. dxe6 fxe6 13. Bc2 Bd6 14. e4 O-O 15.
Bg5
{ This move does not really threaten anything. Black does not mind the exchange. On the other hand it allows Black to force the exchange of White's best minor pieces. Thereafter the Black bishops will be a force to reckon with. }
15... Ne5
{ It is very important to remember that the e5 square is often the route for Black's pieces towards the White side on the board. As a general rule I believe if Black can play Ne5 then Black is better. Conversely the e4-square plays the same role for White. If White can play Ne4 then White is better. }
16. Nxe5
{ Forced: if White moves the Knight then ...Neg4 comes with great force. }
16... Bxe5 17. g3
{ This takes care of the threat to h2 but now the absence of the light squared bishop is a problem. }
17... Qc7
{ This simple move, connecting the rooks, secures an advantage for Black. Black is threatening  h6  after which White has the unpleasant choice of giving the bishop pair with  18.Bxf6  or moving the bishop.   Moving the bishop comes with its own problems, ie.  18.Be3  and Black gives up his bishop pair for the e-pawn by way of  18...Bxc3  followed by  19.bxc3  Bxe4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. The Classical 7 Qe2"]
[Black "Model game #1: Istratescu, Andrei (2587) vs. Aronian, Levon (2645)"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is a nice game where Aronian shows how the quick kingside attack can come from almost nowhere. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e3 a6 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Bb3 Bb7 8. O-O
c5 9. Qe2 Nbd7 10. Rd1 Qb8 11. d5 c4 12. dxe6 fxe6 13. Bc2 Bd6 14. a4
{ Up to here White has played optimally.As so many before him he neglects h3 which is why Aronian can start an attack using the g4- and e5-squares. }
14... O-O 15. axb5 axb5 16. Rxa8 Bxa8 17. Nxb5
{ White has spent several tempi to win the b5-pawn but he completely ignored play on the kingside. Black was no longer playing for the long grinding endgame with the queenside majority. }
17... Bxf3 18. Qxf3 Bxh2+ { Boom. That pawn needed to be on h3! } 19. Kh1 Ne5
{ Notice how the e5-square is a nice launchpad for the kingside attack. } 20.
Qh3 Neg4
{ In the absence of a pawn on h3 Black can make great use of the g4-square. }
21. Bxh7+ { Desperation. } 21... Kf7 22. Rd7+ Ke8 23. Rd2 Qxb5
{ With a few nice tactics Black seals the deal. } 24. f3 c3 25. Bd3 Qb3 26.
bxc3 Qxc3 27. Bc2 Bd6 28. fxg4 Ne4 29. Qh5+ Ke7 30. Qh4+ g5 31. Qh7+ Rf7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. The Classical 7 Qe2"]
[Black "Model game #2: Ehlvest, Jaan (2615) vs. Ivanchuk, Vassily (2700)"]
[Result "*"]

{ If you do not like the idea of playing for the win in the middle game then you could consider the 11... exd5 lines.  This is a good example of grinding for a win in that variation. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 a6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. Qe2 b5 7. Bb3 Bb7 8. O-O
Nf6 9. Rd1 Nbd7 10. Nc3 Qb8 11. d5 exd5
{ In this variation there is usually an exchange of some minor pieces here. Thereafter Black has to endure some pressure due to White's slightly better developed pieces, and if he succeeds in defending he can look forward to a good endgame with his queenside majority. }
12. Bxd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. Rxd5 Be7 15. e4 Qb7 16. Bg5 Nb6
{ Taking the bishop will embarrass Black's king. } 17. Rf5 f6 18. Bh4 O-O
{ Normally if Black gets to castle kingside and nothing bad happens then he is fine. Here he has also played ...f6. Let's see if that is a problem. }
19. e5 Rae8 20. exf6 Bxf6 21. Qc2 Bxh4
{ Following the motto 'less pieces less worries'. } 22. Rxf8+ Rxf8 23. Nxh4 c4
{ I like Black and yes you guessed it: because of that queenside majority. }
24. Nf3 Nd5 25. Ng5 Nf6 26. Re1 h6 27. Nf3 Nd5 28. Ne5 Nf4 29. f3 Re8 30. Re4
Nd3 31. Qe2 Rd8 32. h4 Qb6+ 33. Kh2 Qf6 34. Nxd3 cxd3 35. Re8+ Kf7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. The Materialistic 3...a6 "]
[Black "The Materialistic 3...a6 #1: The Natural 4. a4 but delaying with the e-pawn"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nc3
{ Welcome to Chess Explained's favorite line. This is an alternative line to the Linares Variation and is reached by meeting 3. Nc3 with 3. ... a6. }
3... a6
{ This move is very direct. We want to try and hold on to the pawn by playing b5. }
4. a4
{ This natural push, stopping ...b5, is the most popular approach according to my database. }
4... Nc6
{ Here comes the cavalry to save our c-pawn. Black intends the very straightforward ...Na5. }
5. Nf3
{ In this variation we shall look at a line in which White does not push his e-pawn immediately, instead looking to  (eventually)  play e4 under good circumstances. }
5... Nf6
{ Our plan is simple: we want to play Nf6, e6, Be7 and O-O. At the same time we want to hold on to the c-pawn for as long as possible, making White's life difficult. }
6. Bg5 h6
{ Taking on  f6  with  7.Bxf6  exf6  favours Black because of the two bishops, and it actually gets Black one move closer to castling short. }
7. Bh4 Bg4
{ Often in Queen's Pawn openings Black has to be very careful with moving this bishop on account of Qb3. Here however the c4-pawn controls the b3 square so we can play this move with confidence. }
8. e3 { White now desperately wants that c-pawn and the b3 square. } 8... Na5
9. h3 Bxf3 { Giving the bishop pair but ensuring that we retain the pawn. } 10.
Qxf3 e6 11. Be2 Be7 12. O-O O-O
{ Finally our king is safe and we can direct our attention to the queenside. White can do very little about this. }
13. Rfd1 c6 14. Bg3 b5 { Black is a pawn up and strategically winning. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. The Materialistic 3...a6 "]
[Black "The Materialistic 3...a6 #2: White thinks it is easy to regain the pawn but admits defeat"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nc3 a6 4. a4 Nc6 5. e3 { Attacking the c-pawn. } 5...
Na5 { This defends the pawn and keeps an eye on d4 thanks to Nb3 threats. } 6.
Nf3
{ White goes ahead with the normal Nf3-e5 plan...but is does not work here. }
6... Nf6 { We proceed with development with the idea of a quick 0-0. } 7. Ne5
{ Attacking the c-pawn but no longer protecting d4. This means that if White plays e4 at any stage, as they most often will, Black can easily respond with Nb3 and Qxd4 exchanging the c-pawn for the d-pawn. }
7... Be6 8. Be2 { This move admits that he will not regain the pawn. } 8... g6
9. O-O Bg7 10. Qc2
{ White does not really have a constructive plan here.   10.Bd2  c5  We can even rush our queenside pawn expansion. }
10... O-O 11. Bd2 c5
{ Again the exchange of our extra c-pawn for the White strong d-pawn.  Our plan is simply to proceed with our queenside pawn expansion with a timely b5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. The Materialistic 3...a6 "]
[Black "The Materialistic 3...a6 #3: White plays 4. a4 and then e4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nc3 a6 4. a4 Nc6 5. Nf3 { Defending the d4-pawn. } 5...
Nf6 6. e4
{ White wants to push Black off the board, hoping to regain his pawn that way.   Black has to now give the pawn because after  6...Na5  7.Ne5  there is no good way to defend it. Therefore Black decides not to try and keep it but to use the time to exchange pieces. }
6... Bg4
{ We get to play this move again because of our pawn on c4 covering the b3 square. }
7. Bxc4 Bxf3 { Qb3 was threatened. } 8. gxf3 Qxd4
{ This forces the exchange of either the queens, which would be fatal for White, or the d-pawn for the f-pawn. }
9. Qb3 O-O-O 10. Bxf7 e5
{ From here White has more than one choice but our plan will be the same regardless. We want to exchange into a winning endgame. Specifically our queenside pawn majority supported by our king should be a determining factor. Conversely White's broken pawn majority is restrained by our pawn on e5. }
11. Be3 Qb4 12. O-O Qxb3 13. Bxb3 Nd4
{ White has three choices:  (a)  part with the bishop pair;  (b)  part with his pawn on f3; or  (c)  defend passively with Bd1.Our plan on the kingside is ...g5 followed by Nh5 and Nf4. Thereafter activating our bishop probably Be7 or Bg7. Then doubling our rooks on the d-file. Finally we will proceed with pushing our queenside pawns. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. The Materialistic 3...a6 "]
[Black "The Materialistic 3...a6 #4: White goes 4. e4 and meeting b5 with a4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nc3 a6 4. e4
{ White argues that center control and the minority attack can derail our plans. }
4... b5
{ We have to take up the challenge otherwise White will get everything he wants at no cost. }
5. a4
{ This is the big idea for White. By luring our pawns forward he hopes to attack them later. }
5... b4 6. Na2
{ This move is most popular on master level. Although it seems to win a pawn Black actually has the initiative and will secure an advantage that way.   At club level going forward is more popular but is relatively easy disposed off.     6.Nd5  e6  7.Ne3  Bb7  8.f3  Nc6  9.Nxc4  Qxd4  Once again we exchange our extra c-pawn for the strong White d-pawn. Black is better. }
6... Bb7 { Counter attacking e4. } 7. f3
{ These surprisingly bad moves, Na2 and f3, are actually the most popular in my databases. }
7... Nc6 8. d5 { Dealing with the threat on d4 with tempo. } 8... Na5 9. Nxb4
{ White regains his pawn and feels very good because of our broken structure but wait.... }
9... e6
{ This move reminds us of a certain German chess streamer. Very unassuming but potent. White is immediately forced to give up some material. }
10. Bd2 { 10.Nc6  Nxc6  and the position plays itself. } 10... Nb3 11. Rb1 Nxd2
12. Qxd2 a5 13. Nc2 exd5
{ Black has the two bishops, easy development and will in a few moves have a safe king.  Easy life of a You Tuber. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. The Materialistic 3...a6 "]
[Black "The Materialistic 3...a6 #5: White thinks it is easy to regain the pawn"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nc3 a6 4. a4 Nc6 5. e3 { Attacking the c-pawn. } 5...
Na5 { This defends the pawn and keeps an eye on d4 thanks to Nb3 threats. } 6.
Nf3
{ White goes ahead with the normal Nf3-e5 plan...but this does not work here. }
6... Nf6 { We proceed with development with the idea of a quick 0-0. } 7. Ne5
{ Attacking the c-pawn but no longer protecting d4. This means that if White plays e4 at any stage, as they most often will, Black can easily respond with Nb3 and Qxd4 exchanging the c-pawn for the d-pawn. }
7... Be6 8. e4 Nb3
{ The e4 push always weakens the d4-pawn and this move is the tactical justification for 7... Be6. }
9. d5
{ White goes into the complications because moving the rook will simply lead to the exchange of White's d4-pawn for Black's extra c-pawn. }
9... Nxa1 { This takes us down a long forcing line where Black is not worse. }
10. dxe6 Qxd1+ { Less pieces less worries... } 11. Kxd1 O-O-O+ 12. Ke1
{ White can also go for:   12.Ke2  Nb3  13.Be3  fxe6  14.Nf7  Rg8  15.Nxd8  Kxd8  16.Kf3  Nd7  after which Black is two pawns up. White does have the better structure and two bishops but Black is clearly better. Please note that Nd7 was our novelty. }
12... Nc2+ 13. Ke2 Rg8
{ The key idea for Black is to not take on e6 or otherwise give back the exchange. In this messy position White has to find several precise moves to keep the balance. Our aim is simply to consolidate our material advantage and activate our pieces. }
14. exf7 { 14.Nxf7  Rd4  15.Be3  Nxe3 } 14... Rh8 15. g3
{ Planning to meet ...e6 with Bh3, but... } 15... e6 16. Bh3 Nd7
{ The pawn is tactically defended and we will now proceed to exchange some pieces and eventually capture the f7-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. The Materialistic 3...a6 "]
[Black "Nedoma, Petr (2416) vs. Oudheusden, Willem Adrianus (2349)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nc3 a6 4. e3
{ This modest move does not set the tone for the game to follow. } 4... b5
{ Naturally trying to hold the pawn. } 5. a4
{ This is the only way White can regain the pawn. However White needs to know how to follow up. Other passive moves just don't do it.   5.Nf3  e6  is an improvement for Black because e6 stops the tactical trick. }
5... b4 6. Bxc4
{ This move is made possible by the tactic   6. ...bxc3  7.Qf3 } 6... e6 7.
Nce2 Bb7 { Both sides proceed with normal development. } 8. Nf3 Nf6 9. O-O Nbd7
{ The knight belongs here supporting the c5 push. } 10. b3 Bd6
{ Personally I would have preferred the c5 push hoping that White will oblige and take. However this is ChessExplained's line and he is more subtle than me so ... }
11. Bb2 O-O 12. Ng3 c5 { Development over - now lets break. } 13. Rc1 Qe7 14.
dxc5 Nxc5
{ This move offers the exchange of f6 giving Black the two bishops but paying with his worse structure. }
15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Nd4 f5 17. Be2
{ Black is ever so slightly better after this retreating move.  The game concluded by Black electing to simplify and White co-operating with this. }
17... Bxg3 18. hxg3 Ne4 19. Nc6 Bxc6 20. Rxc6 a5 21. g4 Nc3 22. Qd3 fxg4 23.
Bxg4 Rac8 24. Rxc8 Rxc8
{ The position has simplified dramatically. Black retains some advantage due to his better development. }
25. Bf3 Rd8 26. Qc4 h6 27. Rc1 Rd2 28. Qc8+ Kh7 29. Qc4 Qg5
{ Here the game ended in favour of Black according to the database. It is very probable that the players were in time trouble here, stopped annotating, and White blundered somewhere. The fact is that the White position here is clearly worse and the Black position is easier to play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. The Annoying Variation"]
[Black "The Annoying Variation #1: The Basic endgame "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3
{ Welcome to the Annoying variation.This line annoys White because our play looks too straightforward and there is no clear way to punish Black. Computers like White in most of these lines but practice has favoured Black. }
4... cxd4
{ White has 3 options here:   1  Take with the queen or knight which leads to an endgame which will be won by the player that wants it the most;  2  Take with the bishop which is sharp;  3  Take with the pawn. This is the most popular option and we are going to frustrate White with strange moves that just seem to work. }
5. Qxd4
{ Please note that after  6.Nxd4  e5  7.Nf3  Qxd1+  8.Kxd1  we have an improved endgame. }
5... Qxd4 6. Nxd4
{ Taking with the pawn is just bad. Why go into an endgame with an IQP? } 6...
a6 { We stop Nb5 and threaten ...b5. } 7. Bxc4 e6 { We stop Bd5. } 8. O-O
{ This move reduces the activity of White's king in the endgame.   Please note that in case of  8.Nc3  b5  9.Bb3  Bb7  we are ready to meet  10.a4  with  10...b4  attacking the knight. }
8... Nf6
{ This normal developing move is best.   Instead, after  8...b5  9.Be2!  White will follow up with  a4.  We are not yet ready to meet that attack. }
9. Nc3
{ This is the move we have been waiting for.   If  9.Rd1  Nbd7  we can wait a bit longer before playing ...b5. }
9... b5 10. Be2 Bb7
{ The point is that now  11.a4  b4  comes with gain of tempo.  Black is fine - we want to play Nbd7, Bd6 and Ke7. On a good day Be5 or Ne5 will happen. }
*

