[White "5. The Annoying Variation"]
[Black "The Annoying Variation #2: The improved Endgame"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nxd4
{ This move allows for the improved endgame. } 5... e5 6. Nf3
{ After  6.Nb5  a6  we have a position similar to the Improved Open Endgame in the Grinding Endgames Chapter }
6... Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Nc6
{ This is a very close endgame but Black is slightly better due to more central control. Also the Black bishops can develop easily. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. The Annoying Variation"]
[Black "The Annoying Variation #3: The Sharp line 5. Bxc4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Bxc4 { This is the sharp line. }
5... Qc7 { We attack the bishop. } 6. Qb3
{ Defending the bishop and attacking f7. } 6... e6 { We have to defend. } 7.
exd4
{ This gives White the IQP but frees the bishop.  7.Nxd4  does not make sense because we want to play  7...a6  anyway. }
7... Nc6 { This move means that soon we will have the threat of ...Na5. } 8.
O-O a6 { Immediately losing is  8...Na5 ?  9.Qa4+. } 9. Qe3
{ White deals with the threat of ...Na5 and tries to make d4-d5 work. } 9...
Nf6 { We develop with the idea of looking after d5. } 10. Nc3 Bd6
{ We develop our bishop to the most aggressive square. Black is fine. We will play 0-0, b5 and Bb7. We look forward to attacking the White kingside with moves like Ne5 or winning in the endgame because of the IQP.   Please note the immediate  11.d5  is no good because of  11...Nb4. }
