[White "5. The Annoying Variation"]
[Black "The Annoying Variation #5: The Sharp line 5. Bxc4 revisited."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Bxc4 { This is the sharp line. }
5... Qc7 6. Bb3
{ This is a line I have never had to face. It is however critical and is included for that reason. }
6... dxe3 { Naturally we have to take up the challenge and take the gambit. }
7. Bxe3
{ White has to prove he has enough compensation. Our plan is to try and castle short as soon as possible. If we succeed without anything bad happening then we will have the advantage. }
7... Nf6 8. Nc3 { 8.O-O  will simply transpose. } 8... e6 9. O-O
{ Now we have a real decision to make. Do we want to stop Nb5 with ...a6 or do we want to wait for it and only then play ...a6? }
9... a6 10. Rc1 Nc6 11. Na4 { Aiming for the b6 square. } 11... Bd7 12. Qd2
{ 12.Nb6  Rd8  is easy to play for Black and is equal according to the engines. }
12... Be7 { Black is ready to castle short and is fine. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. The Annoying Variation"]
[Black "The Annoying Variation #6: The fun line 5. exd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. exd4 Be6
{ White has three real moves here. All lines will transpose to one of only two positions, neither of which is bad for us. }
6. Nc3
{ This is by far the most popular move. Please note that both  6.Ne5  Nc6   and  6.Qa4+  Nc6  will transpose. }
6... Nf6 7. Ne5
{ Please note that  7.Qa4  Nc6  transposes   and inserting  7.Bg5?  doesn't work:  7...Nd5  8.Qa4+  Nc6  9.Ne5   Also note  9.Bxc4 ?  Nb6  9...Nxc3!  10.bxc3  Qa5! }
7... Nc6 8. Nxc6
{ In the end we always answer Ne5 with Nc6 and Qa4 with Nc6 or Qa5.   9.Qa4  Qa5! }
8... bxc6 9. Qa4 Qd7 10. Bxc4 Bxc4 11. Qxc4 e6 { Black is better. } *

