[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. exd4 Be6 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Bg5 Nd5 8.
Ne5 { Let's look at the different move order. } 8... Nc6
{ We always meet Ne5 or Qa4+ with Nc6. Simple as that. } 9. Qa4
{ With the inclusion of Bg5 and Nd5 we use the extra tempo to our advantage. }
9... Nxc3 { Exchanging with tempo. } 10. bxc3 Qa5
{ This forces the exchange of queens because we threaten Qxc3 with check. } 11.
Qxa5 Nxa5
{ This position is clearly winning and I have demonstrated it many times online. }
