[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. The Annoying Variation"]
[Black "Tsatsalashvili, K. (2264) vs. Volkov, Sergey1 (2638)"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is a very well played game from the Black side. White's biggest mistake comes on move 15 which allows an attack on the kingside. Then the game goes into a very unbalanced position where Black pays two pawns and an exposed King for a bishop. Black even gives a third pawn to exchange some pieces simplifying the position.    Finally Black starts attacking the two weaknesses  (f2 pawn and the queenside pawns)  whiles keeping his king safe.  This final attack is too much and the White side cannot defend everything and the pawns start falling one by one. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 c5 4. e3 cxd4 5. exd4 Be6 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Ne5 Nc6 8.
Nxc6 bxc6 9. Qa4 Qd7 10. Bxc4 Bxc4 11. Qxc4 e6
{ This is were our line stopped. } 12. O-O
{ White can play  12.Bf4  Be7  and the game will continue along normal lines. }
12... Bd6
{ Volkov develops the bishop to the more aggressive diagonal. Almost as a dare. }
13. Bg5 { White takes up the challenge. } 13... Nd5
{ We cannot allow our structure to be broken. } 14. Rac1 h6 15. Bh4
{ This is the main blunder from White. The alternative is  15.Bd2  Nf6  defending against  Ne4  16.Qe2  O-O  17.Ne4  Nxe4  and the position is equal with both sides having a weakness. }
15... f5
{ Oops... This move embarrasses the bishop and shows why Bh4 was wrong. } 16.
Rfe1 g5 17. Bg3 f4 18. Nxd5 cxd5 19. Qxd5 Kf7 20. Qf3 Kg7 21. Qg4 fxg3 22. hxg3
Rhf8
{ We have arrived at the material balance as mentioned at the start of the game. Black now decides to give a third pawn for a bit more activity and the opportunity to exchange some pieces. Black, correctly, believes that his bishop will rule the day. }
23. Rxe6 Rf6 24. d5 Re8 25. Qd4 Rxe6 26. dxe6 Qxe6 27. Qxa7+ Kg6
{ The position has simplified dramatically and Black has the bishop vs three pawns, including two connected passed pawns on the queenside.  White's problem however is the f2 pawn. He cannot allow Black to penetrate on that square. The finish of the game is Black attacking f2 then the queenside pawns and then f2 again. White's queen and rook simply cannot attend to the threats that Black presents and the pawns fall one by one.   What makes the final moves more impressive is how Black is able to attack the two weaknesses whiles simultaneously protecting his own king. }
28. a4 Qe2 29. b3 Qd2 30. Rf1 Qc2 31. b4 Bxb4 32. Qb8 Qc4 33. Rb1 Bc5 34. Qe8+
Rf7 35. Rf1 Kg7 36. Qe5+ Kh7 37. Qa1 Qc2 38. Qe1 Qxa4 39. Qe2 Qd4 40. Qc2+ Kg7
41. Qe2 Ba7 42. Qc2 Qf6 43. Qd2 Bd4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. The Linares Variation"]
[Black "The Linares Variation #1: The Straightforward 6. Nxb5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nc3
{ This move is common among players who have not prepared QGA and want a nice quite game. Well we will give them a well prepared wild game! }
3... c5
{ Welcome to my 'pet line' This line is best played over the board. The shock on your opponents face when you play 5...b5 makes the line a lot of fun.   The efficiency of the line is also based on the fact that the critical lines are so counter-intuitive that even GMs often misplay this line. Your opponents will underestimate it and take one of the many poisoned pawns and you will come out better. }
4. d5
{ Against almost any other move we will take on d4 with an equal or better position. }
4... Nf6 5. e4 { Now for the surprise: } 5... b5
{ This move defines the Linares Variation after the 1992 Linares tournament where all the best players in the world suddenly took up the line.   Traditional thinking is that Black should not try to hold on to the c4-pawn. However, we are not trying to hold on to the pawn but to counter-attack! }
6. Nxb5
{ This move falls into our plans. We are exchanging our b-pawn for White's e-pawn. }
6... Qa5+ 7. Nc3 { Forced. } 7... Nxe4 8. Bd2
{ 8.Qa4+  Qxa4  9.Nxa4  Bd7  and Black is better. or   After  8.Qc2  the engines like  8. ...Bf5  threatening Ng3  9.Bxc4  Nd7  because the immediate Ng3 runs into Qb3 followed by Qb7  10.Bd2  Just in time and after  Nxd2  we transposed to a position similar to our text save for our bishop that is on f5. If you a strict engine junkie then that is the line to go for. Personally I believe the bishop is misplaced because our target is the d- pawn.   I prefer  8.Qc2  Nd6  at least asking white how he is going to get his pawn back. In reality we know we cannot stop him from getting it back we just want to force him into positions we want to play. White has two reasonable ideas here. After  9.Bf4  we should continue normally and offer the pawn back with  9....Nd7  followed or normal setup placing the bishops on the long diagonal. The sharp  8.Qc2  Nd6  9.Bd2  threatening  Ne4  forces us to play  Bf5  after  10.Qc1  we play  Qa6  and it seems we hold onto the pawn for much longer than expected. The only downside is our misplaced bishop. }
8... Nxd2 9. Qxd2 g6
{ This is my 'novelty' although it has been seen online by lower rated players. }
10. Bxc4 Bg7 11. Nf3
{ White has to choose where to place the knight. Nf3 is more agressive and leaves the e-file open for a rook but in case of   11.Nge2  White's position has more harmony. }
11... O-O
{ Black will continue the same way regardless of where White's knight is placed. We continue with 0-0, Nd7 and Bb7 before considering how to attack. }
12. O-O Nd7 13. Rfe1
{ Here White forces the issue so we have to act immediately. Please note now you will see why we played Nd7 before Bb7. }
13... Nb6 { Fighting fire with fire. } 14. Bb3 c4 15. Bc2 Bb7 16. Rxe7 Bxd5
{ We have exchanged the e-pawn for the d-pawn but we have control over the center. Black is better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. The Linares Variation"]
[Black "The Linares Variation #2: Alternative move order and the book 8. Qf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4
{ The Linares is arrived after both 3. Nc3 and 3. e4. We include this game just show the move order. Thereafter we shall stick to 3. Nc3 because of the challenge between this and the other line. The reader does well to learn this move order because it is the most popular move order into the Linares variation. }
3... c5 4. d5
{ If White does not push we will go into our endgame variations.   4.Nf3  cxd4  and depending on how White recaptures we shall enter the open endgame or the inferior endgame }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 b5 { We're back home... } 6. Nxb5 Qa5+ 7. Nc3 Nxe4 8. Qf3
{ Just a move to be aware of... this is often mentioned in books but very seldom seen. }
8... Nd6
{ We only need to know this move and thereafter White needs to play for tricks to keep the balance. With perfect play the position is equal.   We intend Nd7, Bb7, g6, Bg7 and O-O. }
