[Black "The Linares Variation #6: White fights for the pawn"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nc3 c5 4. d5 Nf6 5. e4 b5 6. e5 b4 7. exf6 bxc3 8. bxc3
Nd7 9. fxe7 Bxe7 10. Bxc4 O-O 11. Ne2
{ This defends the c3 pawn and closes the e-file. Now we have to go full steam for the d5 pawn. }
11... Nb6 { We cannot wait and give White time to consolidate. } 12. Bb5
{ This is White's best try. He immediately loses the d5-pawn after  12.Bd3  Qxd5   or  12.Bb3  c4  13.Bc2  Qxd5. }
12... Bb7 13. Bc6 Bxc6 14. dxc6 Qc7
{ We get our pawn back and we're slightly better developed. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. The Linares Variation"]
[Black "The Linares Variation #7: The testing 9. Bxc4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nc3 c5 4. d5 Nf6 5. e4 b5 6. e5 b4 7. exf6 bxc3 8. bxc3
Nd7 9. Bxc4 Nb6 { Instead, taking on f6 is no good. Take a look for yourself. }
10. Ne2 { The bishop is tactically defended. } 10... exf6
{ Only now that the d6 square is under our control we can take on f6. } 11. O-O
Bd6
{ We blockade the d5-pawn and prepare to castle kingside after which the c4-bishop will be hanging. }
12. Bd3 c4 { This is my novelty. } 13. Bxc4
{ White has to take because leaving the pawn on c4 and keeping White's c- and d-pawns disconnected is just winning for Black. }
13... O-O
{ We need to get our king out of danger.  13...Qc7  - either immediately or after Bxh2+ - is met by  14.Ng3  and thereafter we do not have the time to take on c4 because Re1+ is to strong. }
14. Bd3
{ White does not have the time to protect everything along the c-file. } 14...
Qc7 15. Ng3 Be5
{ Now Black will have the choice which pawn to take. Note: when given the choice and all other things being equal we take the d-pawn. }
