[White "6. The Linares Variation"]
[Black "The Linares Variation #8: The Critical 6. Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nc3 c5 4. d5 Nf6 5. e4 b5 6. Bf4
{ This is the critical test. I have faced it a few times online but never  (in 20 years of playing the variation)  has anyone played it against me over the board.   Please note that against moves like  6.Bg5  we play  6...b4. }
6... Qa5
{ We have to defend the b5-pawn now because Nxb5 would come with the threat of Nc7+. That was the point of Bf4. If you want to go your own way or if you think your opponent is booked up to the nose then you may investigate:   6. ...Ba6  7.e5  b4  8.exf6  bxc3  9.bxc3  Nd7 }
7. e5
{ This is not the only move for White but I give you only our stem game of Gelfand vs Anand 1992 Linares  some sources gives it 1993  which according to some books is one of the best 100 games ever played. The important alternatives are   7.Bd2  Nbd7  8.Nf3  Ng4  where White still has some edge   or  7.a4  Nxe4  8.Ne2  Nd6  9.axb5  Qb6  10.Ng3  Nd7  which is the reason why GM's do not play this variation. }
7... Ne4 8. Ne2 Na6 { This idea is why the game is our stem game. } 9. f3 Nb4
10. fxe4 Nd3+ 11. Kd2 g6
{ It is interesting to see how often this idea is good. To be honest, this is where I got the idea for our Nxb5 lines. }
12. b3 { This move is said to be the inaccuracy. } 12... Bg7 13. bxc4 Nxf4
{ The rest is forced. } 14. Nxf4 Bxe5 15. Ne2 b4 16. Qa4+ Qxa4 17. Nxa4 Bxa1
{ Anand went on to win the game. } *

