1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 c5 4. d5 Nf6 5. Nc3 b5 6. e5 b4 7. exf6 bxc3 8. bxc3
Nd7 9. Bxc4 Nb6 10. Be3 { White decides to counter attack. } 10... exf6 11. Ne2
Bd6 12. Bd3 c4 { This thematic sacrifice is seen so often in these lines. } 13.
Bxc4 O-O 14. Bd3 Qc7 15. Bxb6 axb6 16. h3 f5
{ Black is in no hurry to regain his pawn. } 17. O-O Ra5
{ As always when we can chose between winning the c-pawn and the d-pawn we always prefer the latter. }
18. c4 Be5 19. Rb1 Rxa2
{ White gave the a-pawn to save his central pawns, but has he actually succeeded in saving them? }
20. Qb3 Rd2 21. Rfd1 Rxd1+ 22. Rxd1 f4 23. Bc2 Ba6 24. Qd3 g6 25. Bb3 Rc8 26.
d6 { White has to split the pawns to save the pawns ... for the time being. }
26... Qd7 27. Nc3 Rd8 28. Ne4 Kg7 29. Qd5 f6 30. c5 Bb7 31. Qd3 Qc6 32. Bd5
Qxd5 33. Qxd5 Bxd5 34. Rxd5 bxc5 35. d7 Kf7 36. Nxc5 Ke7 37. Rd1 Bd6 38. Nb7
Rxd7
{ Finally Black wins the d-pawn which he has been chasing since 17... Ra5. }
39. Nxd6 Rxd6 40. Re1+ Kf7
{ now Black has a free roll in a 4 vs 3 rook endgame. } 41. Ra1 g5 42. Kf1 Rb6
43. Ra2 Kg6 44. Ra3 Kh5 45. Ke2 Kh4 46. Kf1 Rb1+ 47. Ke2 h5 48. Kf3 Rb2 49. Ra6
g4+ 50. Kxf4 Rxf2+ 51. Ke3 Kg3 52. hxg4 hxg4 53. Ra4 f5 54. Ra1 Kxg2 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. The Seirawan Variation"]
[Black "The Seirawan Variation #1: The tame 7. exd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3
{ This is probably the most popular move 3 for White. } 3... c5
{ We stick to our normal moves. This is a short chapter in order to tie up some loose ends in our repertoire that occurs after White plays 3. Nf3 and 4. d5. }
4. d5 { 4.e3  transposes to the Annoying Variation. } 4... e6
{ It is important to challenge this pawn immediately. } 5. Nc3
{ 5.e4  will transpose after  5...Nf6. } 5... Nf6 6. e4 exd5
{ 6...b5  is bad because after the straightforward  7.Nxb5  we will never again have the chance to take on d5. }
7. exd5
{ This is a mistake which is made all the time. As will be seen later the critical test is  7.e5  but nobody has ever played it against me over the board. I have only seen it online. }
7... Bd6
{ White has the blockaded IQP. Black has a long-term advantage and is looking forward to a good endgame. He must just get there first. }
8. Bxc4 a6 { This move prevents Nb5 and will later allow ...Qc7. } 9. O-O O-O
{ Both kings go into hiding. } 10. a4
{ This move prevents ...b5 and ...Bb7. I used to think that ...b5 is a really big threat because we get to put early pressure on d5. Now I am less sure about that. The White 'punch combo' as described in the next few moves is very fast and I am not sure that we can spend a tempo on b5. The point is that after   10.Bg5  b5  White plays  11.Bd3!  and all we did was chase the bishop to a more attacking diagonal.  Still if your opponent allows b5 and you want to take the risk then by all means play b5. You may well be rewarded with 11. Be2 where the bishop actually blocks some of the White attack down the e-file. }
10... Bg4
{ 10...Bf5  is a nice try with the idea of keeping some control over e4 but I simply never could make it work. The problem is that White has the 'punch combo' of  11.Bg5  followed by Ne4 which will shatter our pawns in front of our king or worse... }
11. h3 { 11.Bg5  is another try but we play  Nbd7. } 11... Bxf3
{ We part with our bishop but this helps the simplifications. We also gain a half tempo to play Nbd7. }
12. Qxf3 Nbd7 13. Bg5
{ 13.Qd1  Qc7  is equal if not better for Black. See Anand vs. Ivanchuk 2000. }
13... h6
{ I have had this position twice over the board and played  13...Ne5  and ended up drawing both games.  13... h6 is my attempt at improving. Black is equal if not better and the more pieces that come off the better Black will be. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. The Seirawan Variation"]
[Black "The Seirawan Variation #2: The solid 8.Qxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 e6 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. e4 exd5 7. e5
{ This is the best move for White, giving a pawn for the initiative. } 7...
Nfd7 { Black cannot hold on to the d-pawn. } 8. Qxd5 Nb6
{ Black also has nothing better than going into the endgame. } 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ White has a few traps but if Black manages to avoid them he will be fine. }
10. Bg5+ { Developing with tempo. } 10... Be7 { Less pieces, less worries. }
11. O-O-O+ { Development with tempo. } 11... Ke8 { Forced. } 12. Bxe7
{ A major alternative here is  12.Nb5  Na6  13.Nd6+  Bxd6  14.Rxd6  Be6  and we will continue our development. An important point in that final position is that Black can play Nb4-> Nc6 or even Nd5 sometimes. }
12... Kxe7 13. Nd2 Be6 14. f4 Rd8 15. Be2 Nc6 { Black is fine. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. The Seirawan Variation"]
[Black "The Seirawan Variation #3: The Wild 8. Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 e6 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. e4 exd5 7. e5 Nfd7 8. Bg5
{ Hold on to your hat. This is going to be wild. } 8... f6
{ We have to break White's hold on the h4-d8 diagonal. } 9. exf6 gxf6 10. Qxd5
fxg5
{ We have to take the piece sacrifice. Again, it is a case of Black having to survive the traps and if he does so successfully, he will be better. }
11. O-O-O { Threatening Re1+. } 11... Qf6 12. Bxc4 { Threatening Rhe1+. } 12...
Be7
{ Now the initiative turns and Black is better. We threaten Nb6 and are getting our pieces out. Please note that if need be ...Nc6 is a great defensive/development move. }
