[White "7. The Seirawan Variation"]
[Black "Model game #5: Sebenik, Matej (2380) vs. Sermek, Drazen (2603)"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game shows how to grind out the win after the tame 8. exd5. } 1. Nf3 d5
2. d4 c5 3. c4 dxc4 4. d5 e6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a4 Nf6 7. e4 exd5 8. exd5 Bd6 9. Bxc4
O-O 10. O-O Bg4 11. h3 Bxf3
{ As said before this gives up the bishop pair but gains half a tempo. } 12.
Qxf3 Nbd7 13. b3
{ This move is just a wasted tempo. Black goes on to prove how this is enough to grind out the win. }
13... Re8 14. Bg5
{ This comes too late. Specifically with White's queen on f3 Black can now afford to play as follows: }
14... Qe7
{ Black has complete control over the e-file so Ne4 is impossible and the 'punch combo' fails. }
15. g3
{ White makes space for his king in order too contest the e-file but it is to late! }
15... h6 { Our normal move. } 16. Bxf6 Nxf6 17. Rad1
{ If  17.Rfe1  then  17...Qd7. } 17... Rad8 18. Rd2 Qd7 19. Kh2 Be5
{ Black wants to exchange pieces then the d-pawn will become weaker and the queen side majority will become more important. }
20. Re2 Bxc3 21. Qxc3 Nxd5
{ Black wins the d-pawn but some calculation is needed. } 22. Rxe8+ Qxe8 23.
Qf3 Nb6 24. Bd3 c4 25. bxc4 Nxa4 26. Be4 b5 27. Rb1 Nc3 28. Bc6 Qe6 29. Rb3 Ne2
30. Bd5 Nd4 31. Qf4 Qf6
{ Finally White gets the broken pawns on the kingside that he should have gone for with 13. Bg5. In exchange, Black gets the queens off the board. }
32. Qxf6 gxf6 33. Rd3 Ne6 34. Ra3 Nc7 35. Ra5 Nxd5 36. cxd5 Ra8
{ Look at the pawn structure. Black as a very nice queen side majority and a weak d-pawn as a target. White only managed to ruin Black's pawns on the kingside. }
37. Kg2 b4
{ In what follows both players made some mistakes and blunders but in the end it was so good for Black that it was not even that much of a grind... }
38. d6 Kf8 39. Rh5 b3 40. Rxh6 Kg7 41. Rh4 Rb8 42. d7 b2 43. Rg4+ Kh7 44. Rh4+
Kg6 45. Rb4 Rxb4 46. d8=Q b1=Q 47. Qg8+ Kf5 48. Qc8+ Ke4 49. Qxa6 Rb6 50. Qc4+
Ke5 51. Qxf7 Qe4+ 52. Kh2 Qd5 53. Qe7+ Re6 54. Qb4 Qd4 55. Qb8+ Kf5 56. Qb1+
Qe4 57. Qb5+ Kg6 58. Qb8 Kg7 59. Qc7+ Re7 60. Qc5 Rb7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. The Grinding Endgames"]
[Black "The grinding endgames #1: The Modern Endgame"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 c5 4. Bxc4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. O-O a6 7. a4 Nc6 8. dxc5
{ White goes for the endgame. This Chapter is a collection of most of the endgames that may arise from our repertoire. This Chapter needs to be understood rather than be memorized. The exceptions to this is that the reader should always know which move order is best to meet Nb5 or the threat thereof.There are a few lines where we win a tempo or two and it cannot hurt to know when.However these lines are the real grind. Make no mistake: these game will go on for ever. I remember once playing 128 moves of classical over the board chess in one of these variations before finally securing the full point. }
8... Qxd1
{ This is not forced. If you prefer the middle game then  8...Qc7  is a valid option. }
9. Rxd1 Bxc5 10. b3
{ White goes for the modern way of developing the bishop. It does make sense now that there is no more pawn on d4. }
10... b6 11. Bb2 Bb7 12. Nbd2 Ke7
{ This is where the grind begins. The engines prefer White but I prefer Black. Our King is more active. Our main plans are a well timed ...Na5 or ...Ne5 gaining the two bishops or starting a attack on the kingside.   The thing not to do is sit around and wait as Mamedayorv did against Carlsen in 2019 where he was equal but then let it slip away. }
*

