[White "8. The Grinding Endgames"]
[Black "Model game #6: Baginskaite, Camilla (2299) vs. Dlugy, Maxim (2531)"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game is included to show how with some energy even these boring endgames can be won by Black. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 dxc4 4. e4 c5 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4 a6 8.
Bxc4 b5 9. Be2 Bb7 10. a3 Nf6 11. f3
{ Using some pressure against e4 Black has managed to force White into making this passive move. }
11... Nbd7 12. Be3 Bd6
{ Personally I believe the best square for the dark-squared bishop is c5. } 13.
Kf2 Ke7 14. Nb3 Rac8 15. Na5 Ba8 16. Rac1 Rc7 17. Na2 Rhc8
{ White has wasted time with all his knight moves, which allowed Black to establish control over the c-file. }
18. g3 Rc2 { Black has a clear advantage. } 19. Bd4 e5 20. Rxc2 Rxc2 21. Bc3
Bxa3 22. bxa3 Rxa2
{ Black is a pawn up but White has some compensation in the form of the two bishops. }
23. Rd1
{ The grind is on.... From here White will try his best to make it complicated but this famous internet GM knows how to grind. }
23... Kd8 24. Bb4 Kc7 25. Rc1+ Kb6 26. Rc8 Bb7 27. Rc1 Nb8 28. Nb3 Nc6 29. Bc5+
Kc7 30. Rd1 Rc2 31. Ke3 Nd7 32. Bd6+ Kb6 33. Bb4 Bc8 34. Rd6 Nb8 35. Kd3 Rb2
36. Bd1 Kc7 37. Kc3 Rxh2 38. Rd3 Nxb4 39. axb4 h5 40. f4 exf4 41. gxf4 Bg4 42.
Nc5 Bxd1 43. Rxd1 Rh3+ 44. Kb2 h4 45. Rg1 Rg3 46. Rc1 Nc6 47. Nxa6+ Kb6 48. Nc5
Nxb4 49. Nd7+ Kb7 50. Nc5+ Ka7 51. Ra1+ Kb6 52. Nd7+ Kb7 53. Nc5+ Kc6 54. Rc1
Rg2+ 55. Kb3 Rc2
{ In the end we can say he won by grinding it out, piece by piece. Sure there were some small mistakes on both sides but it was the energetic purposeful play that won the day. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. The Grinding Endgames"]
[Black "Model game #7: Banusz, Tamas (2372) vs. Almasi, Istvan (2425)"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game illustrates the title of this course perfectly. White steers the game to a boring endgame. Black plays along by exchanging pieces. Then suddenly White drops a pawn and from there on Black just slowly brings home the point. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 e6 4. e3 Nf6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. dxc5 Qxd1 8.
Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 b6 10. b3 Bb7 11. Bb2 Nbd7 12. Rac1 Ke7
{ Black has developed all the pieces to the right squares. Now he just has to decide where to put the rooks. }
13. Be2 Rhc8 14. Ne5 Nxe5 { Less pieces less worries. } 15. Bxe5 Ne8 16. Bb2 f6
{ Personally I prefer to put the pawns on the lights squares in these endgames: ...g6, ...f5 and then build up to play ...e5 with max central control. }
17. Bf3 Bxf3 18. Nxf3 Rc7 19. Rc2 e5 20. Kf1 Rac8 21. Rdc1 Bb4
{ Less pieces less worries. } 22. Rxc7+ Rxc7 23. Rxc7+ Nxc7 24. Ke2 b5 25. e4
{ White correctly thinks that his pawns belong on light squares. } 25... Ne6
26. g3 Kd6 27. a3 Bc5 28. Ne1
{ This move gives control over the d4-square to Black. } 28... Bd4
{ Now White has to exchange the bishops or give a pawn. } 29. Bc1
{ White decides that his bishop is much better than the black bishop and he gives a pawn to keep the bishops alive. This is a fatal mistake. }
29... Nc5 30. b4 Nxe4 31. f3 Nc3+ 32. Kd3 { So the grind begins... } 32... Nd5
33. g4 Bg1 34. h3 g6 35. Nc2 f5 36. Na1 Nb6 37. Nb3 Nc4 38. h4 Kd5 39. gxf5
gxf5 40. h5 e4+ 41. fxe4+ fxe4+ 42. Ke2 Bb6 43. Na1 Bd4 44. Nb3 Bb6 45. Na1 Ke5
46. Nb3 Kf5 47. Na1 a5 48. bxa5 Nxa5 49. Nc2 Nc4 50. Nb4 Bc5 51. Nc2 Kg4 52. h6
Kf5 53. Kf1 e3 54. Ke2 Ke4 55. Ne1 Bf8 56. Nd3 Bxh6 57. a4 bxa4 58. Nc5+ Kd4
59. Nxa4 Bg5 60. Nb2 Ne5 61. Nd1 Ng4 62. Kf3 e2 63. Bb2+ Kd3
{ And here is were our grinding book ends. GRIND ON :- } *

